# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bashkir-alphabet
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Adamawa Fulfulde was originally brought to Cameroon in the early parts of the 19th century during a religious war (Jihad) that was launched by Usman dan Fodio from Northern Nigeria.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] It is an Atlantic language that belongs to the Niger–Congo language family.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The speakers of the language are the Fulani people.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The language itself is divided into a number of sub-dialects: Maroua, Garoua, Ngaondéré, Kambariire, Mbororoore, and Bilkire.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Sudan, the language is spoken mainly in Blue Nile, Gedaref, and Sennar states with some communities of speakers also found in North Kordofan and South Kordofan states.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In South Sudan, it is spoken in Western Bahr el Ghazal state by Ambororo cattle herders.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Chad, it is spoken in Lac Léré Department in the Mayo-Kebbi Ouest Region.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Nigeria, it is spoken in Adamawa and Taraba states.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] While in Cameroon the language is widespread across the Far North and Northern regions of the country.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The word order for Adamawa Fulfulde is SOV (subject–object–verb).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Adamawa Fulfulde is mostly written in a modified Arabic script, in the tradition of Ajami script, that it shares with many other languages such as Hausa language, and many other languages in Sub-Sahara Africa.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Writing Fulfulde with Arabic script has a long tradition and old manuscripts are found in all of West Africa.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Latin alphabet is also used for writing of Adamawa.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The usage of Latin is a lot more recent, only coming to existence with the arrival of European Christian.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Still, in Cameroon, Arabic alphabet remains more popular for writing of Adamawa Fulfulde than Latin.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The Adamawa Fulfulde Ajami alphabet is the result of many decades of efforts to standardize, starting from the 1960s.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] By the 1990s, the orthography was well established.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In 1998, at the JCMWA/MICCAO conference in Ngaoundéré, Cameroon, over 100 representatives from 14 West African countries agreed that this orthography would be a good standard for writing the Fulfulde language with Arabic script.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The alphabet consists of 33 basic letters, 28 plus *hamaza* from Arabic, and 4 are new letters created for use in Fulfulde.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] 10 of the Arabic letters are only used for writing Arabic loanwords, and have no use for writing indigenous Fulfulde words.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter does come in the beginning of words as a vowel diacritic carrier for common Arabic loanwords.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Character unique to Fulfulde, not found in Arabic.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [θ] in Arabic, but as [s] in Fulfulde.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter is pronounced as [h] in Fulfulde, and is used for representing the sound [h] (except in Arabic loanwords).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The latter is only used in Arabic loanwords in Fulfulde.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [x] in Arabic, but as [h] or [x] in Fulfulde.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter has a variation of pronunciations in different local dialects.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [sˤ] in Arabic, but as [s] in Fulfulde.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [dˤ] in Arabic, but as [d] in Fulfulde.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This is the local indigenous innovation in the Adamawa dialectical area.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Pronounced as [q] in Arabic, but as [k~g] in Fulfulde.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] , in which case it will not carry any diacritic.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter serves two functions, either as a consonant [w], or it lengthens vowels [o] or [u].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] This letter serves two functions, either as a consonant [j], or it lengthens vowel [i].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Letter used for lengthening of vowel [e].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Adamawa Fulfulde, there are 4 prenasalized consonants.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Prenasalized consonants are written as a digraph (combination of two consonants).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The first letter of the digraph representing a prenasalized consonant cannot take any diacritic, including zero-vowel diacritic *sukun* '◌ْ‎'.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Like other languages that have historically been written within what's known as the Ajami tradition, there is a full relaince on diacritics for writing vowels.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Arabic there are only three diacritics, which represent [a] '◌َ‎', [u] [i] '◌ُ‎', and [i] '◌ِ‎'.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] The general tradition is that when there are vowels that don't exist in Arabic, new diacritics are created.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In Adamawa Fulfulde these include the Quranic imāla '◌ٜ‎' for vowel [e], and a special diacritic '◌ٛ‎' for vowel [o].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Unlike Arabic orthography, or other Arabic-derived scripts, in Ajami tradition, all diacritics are written.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Even letters that don't have any vowels, are written with a *zero-vowel/sukun* '◌ْ‎' diacritic.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] Vowels are lengthened by combining the diacritic with a follow-up letter, just as is the tradition in Arabic.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] These follow-up letters are written without a diacritic.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] ' can be part of a digraph representing prenasalized consonants.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adamawa-fulfulde] In these instances, these two letters are written without a diacritic.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe is closely related to the Kabardian or East Circassian language; some reject the distinction between the two languages in favour of both being dialects of a unitary Circassian language, others argue they are closely related but technically distinct languages.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Despite phonological differences, Circassian languages are reciprocally intelligible, with speakers being able to communicate with varying degrees of efficiency.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the self-designation for both Adyghe and Kabardian language is *Adyghe*, in linguistic and administrative terms, "Adyghe" refers specifically to the language of the western tribes of Circassians, while "Kabardian" refers to the language of the two eastern tribes (Kabardians and Besleney).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Ubykh, Abkhaz and Abaza are more distantly related to Adyghe.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe is also known as West Circassian or Lower Circassian.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe belongs to the Northwest Caucasian language family.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Glottochronological studies suggest that the common Proto-Northwest Caucasian language split into the Circassian, Abkhaz, and Ubykh branches roughly 5,000 years ago.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] One of the earliest attempts to create a standard for the Adyghe language was made by Natouko Sheretluk (Natouko Efendi), a Shapsug nobleman.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] He opened a madrasa in his native village of Bogundyr and compiled an Adyghe alphabet and grammar.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Leonty Lyulye, a Russian official who lived for many years among the Shapsugs, Natukhays, and Abadzekhs on the Black Sea coast, published a "Russian-Circassian Dictionary" and a brief grammar in Odessa in 1846.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Lyulye identified three dialects of Adyghe: "Kabardian", "Besleney", and a third he called "Common Circassian" (referring to the Western coastal dialects).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] He tried to base his dictionary on this "Common" dialect.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Another pre-Soviet attempt was made by Wumar Bersey, an Abzakh.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] On March 14, 1853, he published the "Primer of the Circassian Language" (Adyghe Alphabet) in Tiflis (Tbilisi), based on the Arabic script.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] This date (March 14) is now celebrated annually as the "Day of the Adyghe Language".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The standard register of Adyghe, known as Literary Adyghe (Adyghe: Литературабз, lit.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] 'Literature language'), was created by Circassian linguist Daut Ashkhamaf based largely on the Chemguy dialect, which was chosen for its simplicity.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, Literary Adyghe is a constructed dialect and is distinct from the natural Chemguy dialect, as there was significant input from the dialects of other tribes who remained in the Caucasus after the Circassian exile, spesifically the Bzhedug, Shapsug, and partly Abzakh.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the 1930s, Ashkhamaf even utilized the term "Bzhedug-Temirgoy dialect" to describe the basis of the literary language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] He argued that through the development of the literary language, these dialects were merging.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some cases, literary dialect preferred words from other dialects over Chemguy words, such as Bzhedug "ӏэ" (hand) and "тхьэ" (god) instead of the Chemguy "ӏа" and "тхьа", as well as specific ordinal numbers and verb forms.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Thus, being supra-dialectal, literary Adyghe stands in contrast to territorial dialects and serves as the unifying literary form of the language for speakers of diverse dialects.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] There were proposals to merge Adyghe and Kabardian to create a single Circassian literary language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Another proposal was to select one of the two to serve as the single literary language for all Circassians.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] A rejected proposal by Circassian scholars argued for recognizing Kabardian as the sole literary language for all Circassians, as it had the most speakers.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] There were attempts to create a single unified alphabet for Adyghe, Kabardian, Chechen and Karachay-Balkar; but efforts failed because the leaders of the movement were accused of being "bourgeois nationalists" and executed in 1937.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Naloev, who was involved in the creation of the Kabardian alphabet, was executed by firing squad for alleged treason; he was rehabilitated posthumously in 1957.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Bolsheviks supported the creation of separate alphabets and grammars for the "Kyakh" (Western; the modern Adyghe language) and Kabardian, despite ongoing debates on unifying them.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Thus, Adyghe and Kabardian speakers could communicate easier orally as opposed to in writing due to different graphical representations and spelling rules.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] A more moderate proposal developed by the linguist M.A.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Kumakhov aimed to unify the alphabets and orthography without forcing a complete merger of spoken Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] This project proposed standardizing the representation of identical phonemes (using the same letter for the same sound where they currently differ, such as the Adyghe `жъ`vs.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The project was accepted by specialists at regional conferences in Nalchik and Maikop in 1998 and 1999.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the Parliament of the Kabardino-Balkarian Republic approved the project, the Parliament of the Republic of Adygea did not proceed to discuss it.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Cherkess) was a result of Soviet "ethnic engineering".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The International Circassian Association (ICA) officially stated the goal of creating a "uniform Circassian language" in its 2015 congress resolution.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] There are many books written in or translated into Adyghe. А significant milestone was the publication of the "ABC-book of the Circassian language" by Wumar Bersey in Tbilisi on March 14, 1853, a date now celebrated as the Day of the Adyghe Language and Writing.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the early 20th century, reformist movements in Baksan led to the publication of religious and ethical textbooks such as "The History of Islam" (Мыслъымэн Тхыдэ) in 1918.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] A popular Adyghe translation of the Quran was made by Koshbaye Pshimaf Iskhak Mashbash.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The New Testament and many books of the Old Testament have been published in Adyghe by the Institute for Bible Translation in Moscow.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 2020 a bilingual edition of Ecclesiastes was released in Adyghe and Kabardian.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1908, Circassian Union and Charity Society in Istanbul began printing Adyghe language texts in the newspaper *Ghuaze.* Following this, the "*Adığe-Gazete"* (Adyghe Newspaper) was introduced in 1919.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1920, the bulletin "Diyane" was published in Istanbul using a Latin-based Adyghe alphabet.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the Middle East, a Circassian cultural society established in 1927 in El-Quneitra, Syria, published the newspaper "Mardzh" (Voice) from 1928 to 1932.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe Maq is the main Adyghe language newspaper in Russia.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] It is published in the capital of the Adyghe Republic, Maykop, five times a week.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The newspaper *"*Socialist Adygea" started in Krasnodar in 1926 and relocated to Maikop ten years later. he Adigean branch of the Union of Soviet Writers launched the literary almanac "Friendship" in Maikop in 1946.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] For younger readers, the children's magazine *"*Constellation" is published in the Adyghe language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Other early newspapers included *Qerehetlıq* (Black People) in 1924 and *Adığe Psevuç* (Adyghe Life) in 1926.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] According to the UNESCO 2009 map entitled "UNESCO Map of the World's Languages in Danger", the status of the Adyghe language in 2009, along with all its dialects (Adyghe, Western Circassian tribes; and Kabard-Cherkess, Eastern Circassian tribes), is classified as vulnerable.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe exhibits between 50 and 60 consonants depending on the dialect.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] All dialects possess a contrast between plain and labialized glottal stops.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] A very unusual minimal contrast, and possibly unique to the Abzakh dialect of Adyghe, is a three-way contrast between plain, labialized and palatalized glottal stops (although a palatalized glottal stop is also found in Hausa and a labialized one in Tlingit).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Shapsug (Black Sea) dialect of Adyghe contains a very uncommon sound: a voiceless bidental fricative [h̪͆], which corresponds to the voiceless velar fricative [x] found in other varieties of Adyghe.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] This sound is only known to be used in the Black Sea dialect.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the Black Sea coast Adyghe dialects (e.g.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Shapsug dialect and Natukhai dialect) there exist a palatalized voiced velar stop [ɡʲ], a palatalized voiceless velar stop [kʲ] and a palatalized velar ejective [kʲʼ] that were merged with [d͡ʒ], [t͡ʃ] and [t͡ʃʼ] in most Adyghe dialects.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] For example the Shapsug words "гьанэ" [ɡʲaːna] "shirt", "кьэт" [kʲat] "chicken" and "кӏьапсэ" [kʲʼaːpsa] "rope" are pronounced in other dialects as "джанэ" [d͡ʒaːna], "чэт" [t͡ʃat] and кӏапсэ [t͡ʃʼaːpsa].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In contrast to its large inventory of consonants, Adyghe has only three phonemic vowels in a vertical vowel system.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Adyghe alphabet contains some inconsistencies between visual representation and pronunciation which can be a point of confusion for learners.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] It is tempting to read the Circassian alphabet letters phonologically, but this is not always accurate.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] These letters are not part of the official alphabet, but they may appear in books that showcase the different dialects.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] For most of its history, Adyghe was an oral language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The folklore, particularly the Nart sagas, served as a repository for the language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Widespread literacy in Adyghe did not exist until the modern era and literacy was limited to a few people.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] From the 6th–5th centuries BC until the first half of the 15th century, the Adyghe people used the Greek alphabet, initially introduced through ancient Greek colonies and later reinforced by the Byzantine Empire and the Christian church.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Early forms of the Cyrillic alphabet were also used during this period due to Russian influence.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] During the 13th to 15th centuries, the development of relations with the Genoese Republic led to some use of the Italian (Latin) script.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the 14th century, along with Islam, the Arabic script was adopted for Adyghe.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] It was referred to as Ajam**,** a writing system for the native language based on the Perso-Arabic script.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Since Adyghe has many more consonants than Arabic, the Ajam system required adding special diacritical marks or inventing new letters to represent sounds.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Early attempts to write Adyghe in modern Cyrillic started as early as 1829 and were followed by similar attempts.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1853, the Adyghe educator Umar Bersey published the first "Primer of the Circassian Language" based on the Arabic script.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Over the following decades, several authors attempted to further improve the Adyghe Arabic orthography.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The most successful attempt was the alphabet created by Akhmetov Bekukh.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In this version, letters were designated for vowel sounds, and the orthography was transformed from an "Impure abjads to a true alphabet.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1918, on the initiative of the Kuban Revolutionary Committee, a primer was published in Yekaterinodar.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] This official endorsement resulted in a literary boom in Adyghe and the publication of various newspapers, textbooks and other literature, including the *Adyghe Maq*, the main Adyghe language newspaper established in 1923.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] During the abovementioned decades, parallel with this process, the Perso-Arabic orthography had also been standardized for the sister Circassian language of Kabardian.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Although very similar in many aspects, there were minor variations, in which letters were included based on each respective phonology, and there were minor differences in presentation of a few consonants as well.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Arabic script was used until 1927, when as a part of the Soviet "Latinisation" campaign, a Latin-based alphabet was adopted.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Yakovlev and the Adyghe scholar Daud Ashkhamaf.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the late 1930s, the script was converted to Cyrillic to align with Russian.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the diaspora, a new Latin alphabet based on the Turkish alphabet was designed to better facilitate Adyghe and Kabardian education in Turkey, named the ABX alphabet.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe, like all Northwest Caucasian languages, has a basic subject–object–verb typology and is characterised by the ergative construction of sentences.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Turkey hosts the largest Circassian population, but the language lacks any legal recognition.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, after the collapse of the Ottoman Empire and the establishment of the modern republic, these schools were banned by the Kemalists.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Following the "Citizen, Speak Turkish!" campaign and the closure of Circassian schools, the language was confined to the home.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In educational settings, speaking Adyghe was strictly banned.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Students faced physical punishment and psychological alienation for speaking Adyghe, including during recess and outside of school grounds.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] To enforce this, teachers formed "discipline committees" made up of student informants.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Publishing in the language also faced state pressure; cultural magazines had to remove Circassian lyrics from traditional songs and publish only the musical notes to avoid government retribution.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Consequently, while the older generation retains fluency, proficiency among those under 50 is significantly diminished.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In a study, Nusret Baş (Бажь Нусрэт), the then-president of the Federation of Circassian Associations, estimated that about 5% of Circassians in Turkey (including people of Circassian descent) speak their native language fluently.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Linguistically, the Adyghe spoken in Turkey exhibits distinct features as it was not subject to the standartisation policies in the Caucasus.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] It contains archaic vocabulary lost in the Caucasus, alongside Turkish loanwords.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the Chemguy dialect forms the basis of the literary language in the Republic of Adygea, the majority of the diaspora in Turkey speaks the Abzakh and Shapsug dialects (as well as Kabardian), alongside smaller numbers of Bzhedug and Hatuqay speakers.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Hatuqay dialect is spoken only in Turkey.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some cases, the physical mixing of different tribes led to dialectal convergence.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Frequent intermarriages between dialect groups led to the use of a mixed Adyghe koine or the dominance of one dialect in multi-tribal areas.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some cases, the boundaries between dialects became blurred, resulting in a hybrid oral communication style, sometimes even including hybrids with Kabardian or Abaza.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Due to assimilation, Adyghe speakers in Turkey sometimes use Turkish terms for numbers, days of the week, months, and colors.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Significant changes occurred following Turkey's European Union accession process in the early 2000s.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The language policy was liberalized, which prompted revival efforts.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 2012, the Ministry of National Education introduced "Living Languages and Dialects" as an elective course for secondary schools, allowing Adyghe to be taught in public schools.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Classes are only opened if a set minimum number of students apply, and bureaucratic hurdles regarding application windows often hinder access to these classes.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Teachers are subject teachers with basic language skills rather than trained philologists, and they receive limited training in language pedagogy.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Educational materials are imported from Adygea and are designed for native speakers, making them difficult to adapt for diaspora students who are learning Adyghe as a second language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] During the COVID-19 pandemic, transnational online courses were organized in collaboration with institutions in Russia, allowing students in Turkey, Jordan, and Germany to be taught by teachers directly from the Caucasus.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Düzce University has a Department of Caucasian Languages and Cultures, which offers "Circassian Language and Culture" programs, including the teaching of Adyghe in Cyrillic, as the surrounding region is inhabited largely by Shapsug and Abzakh Circassians.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Boğaziçi University began offering elective Adyghe courses in 2013.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] A significant debate persists in the Turkish diaspora regarding orthography of Adyghe.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Federation of Caucasian Associations (KAFFED) adopted the Cyrillic alphabet in 2004 to maintain continuity with the homeland, but other groups advocate for a Latin-based script to facilitate easier learning for Turkish speakers.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] This dispute intensified significantly when the Turkish Ministry of Education approved a Latin-based alphabet, called the ABX Latin Alphabet, for elective Circassian language courses in public schools, effectively creating a dual-alphabet system alongside the existing Cyrillic curriculum.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] KAFFED vehemently opposed this decision, arguing that it creates confusion and severs cultural ties with the autonomous republics in the Caucasus.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Demonstrations were at Ministry of Education offices across the country with slogans including "Hands off my alphabet," "We want our mother tongue's alphabet" and "How does Arabic in Latin letters sound?".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Ubykh people in Turkey, who originally possessed their own distinct language, largely integrated with the Adyghe during their exile and adopted the Adyghe language as their own.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Ubykh language went extinct in 1992; today Ubykh people speak Adyghe or Turkish.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe State University is working to document Adyghe language and folklore in Turkey.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian community in Israel, concentrated in the Circassian towns of Kfar Kama and Rehaniya, is considered to have one of the highest levels of language maintenance in the diaspora.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe serves as the language of daily communication in the home, school, and public spaces.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1958-1959, Israeli Circassians made contact for the first time with Circassians in the Caucasus and requested literary material in Adyghe, which they received.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In 1976, the Adyghe language was introduced into the official school curriculum.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] It is a compulsory subject from 6th grade onward, and utilizes textbooks based on the literary standard of the Republic of Adygea.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Despite the dominance of the Shapsug dialect in speech, the written language taught in schools utilizes the Cyrillic alphabet and the Chemguy-based literary standard.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Kfar Kama is inhabited by the Shapsug tribe, while Rihaniya is inhabited by the Abzakh tribe.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Israeli variety of Adyghe also contains unique neologisms.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Even in diaspora communities with highly preserved spoken fluency, such as the compact Circassian settlements in Israel, literacy is a significant challenge; one survey showed that while 81.7% of respondents had advanced speaking proficiency, only 12% reported writing proficiency.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In Jordan, the Adyghe language has historically enjoyed a relatively privileged status, though it currently faces significant pressure, as Arabic has become the dominant language for the younger generation, and the Adyghe language is often restricted to symbolic functions or domestic use.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Consequently, Adyghe in Jordan serves more as a folkloric marker of identity than a functional tool for daily communication.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Adyghe language in Jordan is currently classified as severely endangered due to a rapid disruption in intergenerational transmission.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The decline of the language was triggered by migration, urbanization, and the dispersion of the Circassian population among the Arabic-speaking majority.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] For example, the expansion of Amman in the early 1900s transformed predominantly Circassian farming villages into diverse urban centres inhabited by Arabs, causing Circassians to become a minority in their original settlements.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Today, Arabic has almost entirely ousted Circassian as the primary language of communication within the home.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Surveys indicate that 21% of children use Circassian at home.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Because schools historically used Arabic as the sole medium of instruction, Circassian parents began speaking Arabic at home to ensure their children would not struggle academically.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Adyghe is taught in Prince Hamza Ibn Al-Hussein Secondary School, a school for Jordanian Circassians in Jordan's capital city of Amman.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] This school, established by Circassians with support from King Hussein of Jordan, is one of the first schools for the Adyghe communities outside Circassia.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] It has around 750 Jordanian Adyghe students, and aims to preserve the Adyghe language and traditions among future generations.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The diaspora in Jordan has produced dictionaries and linguistic works, such as a Circassian-Arabic dictionary published in 1988.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian Charity Association of Jordan also sponsors a school between Naur and Wadi Al-Seer that teaches the language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Historically, various dialects were spoken by immigrants, including Shapsug, Bzhedug, (and Kabardian), but over time these dialects have merged.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Historically, the Golan Heights served as a centre for Circassian language preservation prior to the 1967 war.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the 1920s and 1930s, the "Circassian Society of Education and Union" in Quneitra published the newspaper *Mardj* in Circassian (using the Latin script), Arabic, and French, and established a school that taught the language alongside general subjects.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In the late 20th century, the Circassian Charity Association in Damascus operated informal language circles to teach the Cyrillic script and preserve oral traditions.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, the language has declined due to the lack of state-supported education and the dominance of Arabic in all public spheres.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] After the Syrian defeat in the war, the Circassian population largely fled the Golan Heights region, which was occupied by the Israeli Army.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Many of Syria's ethnic Circassians have left the country and have repatriated to Adygea, Kabardino-Balkaria and Karachay-Cherkessia, as well as to partially recognised Republic of Abkhazia.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian American community is multilingual, speaking languages including English, Circassian (Adyghe, Kabardian), and Arabic.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, the community is currently experiencing a significant language shift away from their ethnic Adyghe language and toward English.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] English is the dominant language used in almost all public and social domains, utilized universally in the workplace and overwhelmingly with neighbors, non-Circassian friends, and even among Circassian peers.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Adyghe language remains preserved primarily within the home, specifically in intergenerational communication.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Circassian is predominantly spoken by the elder members of the community and is the primary language used when younger generations address their grandparents, representing over 52% of these interactions.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] A study found that a large majority of the New Jersey Circassian community (81.5%) agrees that learning the Circassian language is essential for maintaining their ethnic identity.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] However, some Circassian Americans have abandoned Adyghe fluency as redundant, focusing instead on Adyghe Khabze, traditional dances and folklore.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The Circassian Benevolent Association (CBA) hosts a Sunday school where volunteers teach the Circassian language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In recent years, growing political pressure and the criminalization of civil society initiatives in Russia have forced many scholars and language activists to relocate, shifting the epicenter of Circassian language activism and cultural preservation to countries abroad, including the United States.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Following the Circassian Genocide and expulsion in 1864, the majority of Adyghe speakers were scattered across the Ottoman Empire.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The language spoken in the diaspora has diverged from the literary forms in the Caucasus.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Diaspora communities often use Arabic or Turkish loanwords where the literary language uses Russian ones.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The linguistic divergence between the Adyghe language spoken in the historical homeland and the language spoken by the diaspora, particularly in Turkey and the Middle East, is the result of over a century and a half of isolated development.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] This isolation, combined with the mixing of various dialects and the strong influence of local languages like Turkish and Arabic, led to significant phonetic, lexical, and semantic differences.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Some native Adyghe words acquired entirely new meanings in the diaspora.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The word *гу*, which historically means "wagon" or "cart" in the literary language, has evolved to mean "automobile" or "car" among diaspora speakers.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Similarly, the word *ин* (big) is used in the diaspora to refer to an "elder," replacing the literary term *нэхъыжь*.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Due to intense influence of the Russian language, Russian loanwords in standart Adyghe are left exactly as is and not adapted to the language in terms of spelling or pronouncation.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Turkish linguistic influence led to the creation of calques (literal translations) for modern concepts.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In some extreme cases, diaspora speakers even attach Turkish grammatical suffixes, such as the past tense *-miş* or the subjunctive *-dı*, directly to Adyghe roots, though native speakers often recognize these constructions as "non-Adyghe".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] While the spoken and folkloric language of the diaspora evolved independently, this isolation has begun to diminish.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] With the advent of the internet and social media, the younger and middle generations in the diaspora are increasingly interacting with the Cyrillic-based literary language of the homeland.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] This exposure is initiating a slow but inevitable "literaturization" of the diaspora's language, gradually aligning their written and official communication with the literary standard.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] When conversing in Turkish, diaspora Circassians frequently embed native Adyghe terms to refer to specific traditional and unique cultural conventions, or use them as in-group slang.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Besides native vocabulary, the Adyghe language has accepted loanwsome ords from Turkic, Arabic, Persian, Russian and other languages.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] The appearance of Turkic loanwords in the Adyghe language can be dated to the 14th century due to interactions with the Golden Horde and Crimean Khanate.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] By the mid-19th century; Arabic words had begun to enter the language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] Words such as *chapych* (kopeck) are pre-revolutionary loans from Russian.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/adyghe-language] In old borrowings, as a rule, the phonetic composition of borrowed words was adapted to the phonological system of the Adyghe language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aer-language] After the Partition of India in 1947, the Muslim speakers of the language migrated to Pakistan, while the Hindu speakers stayed in India.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aer-language] Most of the Aer speakers in Pakistan live in Deh 333, near Hyderabad in lower Sindh.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aer-language] The language was formed in the Indian subcontinent during the Delhi Sultanate and Mughal Empire due to the influence of Persian, Arabic, and Turkish on Indian languages.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aer-language] A 1998 estimate concluded there were around 200 native speakers.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aer-language] Current estimates, however, put the number of speakers at 150, further cementing its 'endangered' status.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aer-language] Aer has been classified as one of the Gujarati languages.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aer-language] Ethnologue reports that the closest language is Kachi Koli and especially its dialects Katai Meghwar and Kachi Bhil, and that most Aer speakers are bilingual in Sindhi.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aer-language] Two varieties of Aer are Jikrio Goth Aer and Jamesabad Aer.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aer-language] Aer is commonly not written, but when it is, it is written in a variety of the Arabic script.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/afshar-dialect] Afshar is distinguished by many loanwords from Persian and a rounding of the phoneme /a/ to [ɒ], as occurred in Uzbek.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/afshar-dialect] In many cases, vowels that are rounded in Azerbaijani are not rounded in Afshar.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/afshar-dialect] An example of this is /jiz/ (meaning *100*), which is /jyz/ in standard Azerbaijani.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Air Tamajeq, as well as other Tuareg languages, has traditionally and recently been written in three orthographies, with one or the other being the dominant orthography in specific contexts.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] These are Arabic script, Latin script, and Tifinagh (Traditional Tamajeq Tifinagh) script.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Tifinagh has been the ancient and traditional script for writing of Tuareg.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] However, as Tuareg peoples have been a largely oral society, Tifinagh has only been used primarily for games and puzzles, short graffiti and brief messages.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Arabic alphabet has come to be adopted with the spread of Islam among Tuareg people from the 7th century onward.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Tuareg people, being an integral part of the Trans-Saharan trade, played the most significant role in spreading Islam to indigenous African communities further south, in the Sahel and Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Thus, Tuareg merchant, scholars, and clerics played a significant role in the teaching of the Arabic alphabet and its eventual adoption as part of what's today known as Ajami convention of writing, for writing of languages such as Songhay, Fula, and Hausa.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Latin has been used for writing of Air Tamajeqand other Tuareg languages a lot more recently.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Latin-derived scripts have been developed and adopted since the 19th century with the arrival of European Christian missionaries, colonial administrators, and linguists.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] The Latin script for Air Tamajeq is an "Alphabet".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Tuareg languages, including Air Tamajeq, are the only languages that use Tifinagh in its original traditional form.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] The Traditional Tifinagh script is an "Abjad", meaning that vowels are not written or shown in any way, neither are geminated consonants.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Only in the final position do letters *a* (ⴰ), *w* (ⵓ), *y* (ⵢ) serve as vowels in some contexts.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Elsewhere, for example among the Imazighen (Berbers), the modified neo-Tifinagh, which is a full alphabet, is used.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] The Arabic script is an "Impure Abjad", meaning that some vowels are written using diacritics and some using actual letters, consonant letters serving as vowels depending on the context.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/air-tamajeq-language] Below is a sample text, translation of the Holy Bible, specifically the Gospel of Luke, chapter 1, verses 1 to 4 into Air Tamajeq.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] The term is derived from earlier designations, such as *lingua turcica agemica*, or *Turc Agemi*, which was used in a grammar book composed by the French writer Capuchin Raphaël du Mans (died 1696) in 1684.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Local texts simply called the language *türkī*.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] During "the Isfahan phase of the Safavids", it was called *ḳızılbaşī* in contrast to *rūmī* (Ottoman) and *çaġatā’ī* (Chagatai), due to its close relation to dialects spoken by the Qizilbash.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Ajem-Turkic is descended from Old Anatolian Turkish, and is part of the southwestern branch of Oghuz languages.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] The language first appears during the 15th-century in Azerbaijan, eastern Anatolia, and Iran.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Under them, Ajem-Turkic, alongside Persian, was used at the court and in the military, and was a *lingua franca* from northern to southern Iran.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] According to Swedish Turkologist Lars Johanson, Ajemi Turkic was an "Azerbaijanian koiné" that functioned as *lingua franca* in the Caucasus region and in southeastern Dagestan, and was widely spoken at the court and in the army.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Ajem-Turkic had already emerged as both a spoken and written language during the fifteenth century under the Aq Qoyunlu and Qara Qoyunlu states.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Following 1500, however, the language evolved into a supraregional variety extending beyond Azerbaijan itself and functioning across a wider geographical area.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] This development took place within the broad region centered around political hubs such as Isfahan.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Prominent representatives of early Ajem-Turkic literature include poets such as Jahan Shah, Imadaddin Nasimi, and Muhammad Fuzuli.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Ajem-Turkic functioned as a lingua franca in the Caucasus and southeastern Dagestan.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] It was widely used within governmental circles and the military.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] During the Safavid period, the majority of soldiers reportedly spoke only this language and had no knowledge of Persian.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Recording his observations in 1617–1618, the Italian traveler Pietro della Valle noted that Ajem-Turkic differed from Ottoman Turkish and contained numerous “Tatar,” that is, eastern Turkic, lexical elements.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Nevertheless, scholarly knowledge of Ajem-Turkic or Middle Azerbaijani remains limited, as only a small number of texts have been subjected to linguistic analysis.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Bellér-Hann examined the Tarikh-i Khatai, dating from 1494–1495.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] In the sixteenth century, several works were translated into Ajem-Turkic by Muhammad al-Katib, known as Nishati Shirazi.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] One of these was the Shuhadanama, a 1538 translation of Husayn Va'iz Kashifi’s Persian work Rawzat al-Shuhada, originally composed in 1502–1503.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] The work contains narratives and legends concerning Ali ibn Abi Talib and the martyrs of Karbala.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Another important translation was the Kitab-i Tazkira-i Shaykh Safi, completed in 1542, which was based on Safvat al-Safa, written by Ibn Bazzaz in 1358.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] This work recounts the life of Shaykh Safi al-Din.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Both works are regarded as important Shiʿi texts.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Nishati explained that the purpose of these translations was to benefit Turkic students, Sufis, mullahs belonging to Turkic tribes, and the people of Turkestan who lacked knowledge of Persian.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Among the political figures who encouraged this undertaking during the reign of Shah Tahmasp I were the Qizilbash official Shahqulu Khalifa Zulkadar, who held high-ranking positions in Tabriz and Qazvin at the Safavid court, and Qazi Khan Takalu, governor of Shiraz.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Since its appearance, Ajem-Turkic was heavily impacted by Persian, especially in its syntax.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] The Persian design of merging clauses which Ajem-Turkic had inherited from Old Anatolian Turkish was strengthened due to its continuous contact with Persian.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/ajem-turkic] Sources for the study of Ajemi-Turkic include the prose texts of Nishati (fl.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Chejne, *Aljamiado* or *Aljamía* is "a corruption of the Arabic word *ʿaǧamiyyah* (in this case it means foreign language) and, generally, the Arabic expression *ʿaǧam* and its derivative *ʿaǧamiyyah* are applicable to peoples whose ancestry is not of Arabian origin".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] During the Arab conquest of Persia, the term became a pejorative.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The systematic writing of Romance-language texts in Arabic scripts appears to have begun in the fifteenth century, and the overwhelming majority of such texts that can be dated belong to the sixteenth century.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] A key *aljamiado* text is the compilation *Suma de los principales mandamientos y devediamentos de nuestra santa ley y sunna* by the muftī of Segovia, of 1462.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In later times, Moriscos were banned from using Arabic as a religious language, and wrote in Spanish on Islamic subjects.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Examples are the *Coplas del alhichante de Puey Monzón*, narrating a *Ḥaǧǧ*, or the *Poema de Yuçuf* on the Biblical Joseph (written in Aragonese).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Aljamiado played a very important role in preserving Islam and the Arabic language in the life of the Moriscos of Castile and Aragon; Valencian and Granadan Moriscos spoke and wrote in Andalusi Arabic.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] After the fall of the last Muslim kingdom on the Iberian peninsula, the Moriscos (Muslims in parts of what was once Al-ʾAndalus) were forced to convert to Christianity or leave the peninsula.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] They were forced to adopt Christian customs and traditions and to attend church services on Sundays.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Nevertheless, some of the Moriscos kept their Islamic belief and traditions secretly, and this included the usage of Aljamiado.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In 1567, Philip II of Spain issued a royal decree in Spain, which forced Moriscos to abandon using Arabic on all occasions, formal and informal, speaking and writing.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Using Arabic in any sense of the word would be regarded as a crime.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] They were given three years to learn the language of the Christian Spanish, after which they would have to get rid of all Arabic written material.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Moriscos of Castile and Aragon translated all prayers and the (ʾAḥādīṯ of the Prophet Muhammad) into Aljamiado transcriptions of the Spanish language, while keeping all Qurʾānic verses in the original Arabic.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Aljamiado scrolls were circulated amongst the Moriscos.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Historians came to know about Aljamiado literature only in the early nineteenth century.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Some of the Aljamiado scrolls are kept in the Spanish National Library in Madrid.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] It is not an independent letter, but a special "dongara" consisting of a letter and a consonant (in other words, the repetition of a letter) to indicate a specific sound.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] These letters are only used in writing Arabic loanwords.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The Ladino equivalents for these letters are in accordance with the Judeo-Arabic orthographic traditions.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] This letter has a dual pronunciation, depending on the letter after it.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] For this reason, both in Aljamiado and in Ladino, two different letters are used to represent it.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Ladino, the pronunciation of this letter differs from its equivalent in modern Spanish.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Whenever the letter "D" is at the beginning of the word, or after a nasal consonant ("m" or "n"), or after a lateral consonant ("l"), pronounced as [d] and written with the letter "d".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In all other cases, it is pronounced as [ð] and written with the letter "d".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, the letter "X" was for representing the sound [ʃ].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] But in some words, especially those that start with "ex-", the pronunciation of this letter is [s], [ks] or [gz].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In the writing of Aljamiado, the Maghrebi script has been common, in which the placement and number of dot of on letters "fāʾ" and "qāf" are different from the conventional Arabic script, or the so-called "*Mashriqī* script" (مشرقي).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "wāw" does not correspond to any exact letter in the Spanish Latin alphabet.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] This letter and its sound [w] are pronounced in certain digraphs and trigraphs.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Worded differently, there are diphthongs and triphthongs as result of certain vowel sequences, where the sound [w] is pronounced and the letter "wāw" is used to write it.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "y" in the Spanish Latin alphabet is equivalent to "yāʾ" (ي).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] But this letter is also used to write some consonant sequences, especially consonant sequences that have a sound similar to [j] in their pronunciation.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In the Arabic language and alphabet, however, there are only 3 vowels, [a], [i], [u].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Arabic, these 3 vowels have both a short form, which is represented by diacritics *fatʾha*, *kasra*, and *ḍamma*, and long forms, which are represented by the letters *alif* (ا), *yaʾ* (ي), and *waw* (و).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish, however, there is no difference between short and long vowels.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The vowel [a] is represented by the diacritic "◌َ".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The vowel [i] is represented by the diacritic "◌ِ".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The two vowels [o] and [u] are merged and are represented by the diacritic "◌ُ".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The vowel [e] is represented by the combination of fatʾha and *alif* "ـَـا".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The Hebrew alphabet, like Arabic, has both diacritics, known as niqqud, and the use of three letters *alef* (א), *vav* (ו), and *yod* (י).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In the Judaeo-Spanish alphabet, niqqud is not used, and only three aforementioned letters are used.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The vowel [a] is represented by *alif* "א".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The two vowels [e] and [i] are merged and represented by *yod* "י".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The two vowels [o] and [u] are merged and are represented by *vav* "ו".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Aljamiado, similar to Arabic and Persian, when the vowel is at the beginning of the word, *alif* (ا) is used as the vowel carrier, except for the [e] sound.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] For the [e] sound, a hamza is used as a vowel carrier, followed by *alif* (ا).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judaeo-Spanish (Ladino) as in Arabic, *alif* "א" plays the same role.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] No distinction between unstressed or stressed vowels exist in Aljamiado manuscripts.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In the middle of the word, in Aljamiado, only diacritics (and for the case of [e] only a diacritic and an *alif* (ا) and in Judaeo-Spanish only one of the three previously mentioned letters are used.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish, vowels sequences fall into two general types, diphthongs and Vowel hiatus.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] "diphthong" means that in practice, a pair of sequential vowels are read as a single vowel under one syllable.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] "Vowel hiatus" means that two vowels are read as two consecutive separate syllables.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The pronunciation of vowels and their writing are subject to certain rules in the Spanish Latin Alphabet, as well as in Aljamiado.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] As previously mentioned, in Aljamiado, there is no difference in writing between [o] and [u].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judaeo-Spanish, there's no difference between [o] and [u], nor between [e] and [i].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] "Vowel hiatus" occurs when two strong vowels are sequential.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In such a case, each vowel is read as part of a separate syllable.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] "Diphthong" occurs when one vowel is weak and the other is strong.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In this case, Stress in pronunciation is on the strong vowel.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Of course, there are exceptions to these rules.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In order to better understand Aljamiado writing conventions, it is necessary to understand the pronunciation of Old Spanish and the evolution of the sounds of Spanish.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] That is why the manuscripts of Aljamiado are considered important sources for the study of Spanish linguistics.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The first thing that should be mentioned is that in Aljamiado, like Persian and other Arabic-derived alphabets, changes were made to the letters in the Arabic alphabet in order to show new consonants.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In other Arabic-derived alphabets, these changes were made by adding dots to the letters that most closely match an existing sound in Arabic alphabet.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] But in Aljamiado, this was done by gemination mark on the letters with the closest existing sound.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Gemination, in addition to this role, in Aljamiado also plays the role of geminating, like Arabic, something that is done in the Spanish Latin alphabet by writing letters twice.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] For example, "ب" produces a [b], but "بّ" produces a [p].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The Ladino alphabet also does the same thing with niqqud such as "Rafe" (רָפֶה) "◌ﬞ" or "Geresh" (גֶּרֶשׁ) "◌׳", for example "ב" produces the sound [b], and "בﬞ" or "ב׳" produce the sound [v].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Some letters simply adopted another value.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The phoneme /β/ was typically represented by the letter ب (b), though in some instances it was represented by the letter ف (f).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The plosive consonants were required to be aspirated; however, this aspect was lost in weaker positions such as the initial position of a word or an intervocalic position.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Aljamiado texts, the letter ط was utilized to represent the phoneme /t/ in initial and intervocalic positions where it was unaspirated, while the letter ت was utilized in postconsonantal positions to indicate the aspirated form of the phoneme.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Similarly, the letter ﻕ was used to represent the phoneme /k/ in initial and intervocalic positions where it was unaspirated, and the letter ﻙ was used in postconsonantal positions to indicate the aspirated form.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] However, according to the glossary of Abuljair, the aspiration of plosive consonants never ceased to occur in any position.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish language, the letter "B" has two allophones.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] If the letter is at the beginning of the word, or after a nasal consonant ("m" or "n"), it is pronounced as [b].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "v" also is pronounced as [v~β] regardless of position in the word.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Aljamiado, no distinction is made between any one of these.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "baʾ" (ب) is used for all cases.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish, distinction is made between these two allophones.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Cases of [b] are written with the letter "beth" "ב".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Whereas the sounds [v~β] are written with the letter "beth" with Rafe or Geresh "בﬞ (ב׳)".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] As Arabic alphabet lacks a letter for the equivalent to the letter "P", the sound [p], in Aljamiado, a digraph has been created.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] This digraph consists of the letter "baʾ" and a shadda, "بّ".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] This is not an issue in Judeo-Spanish, as the letter "Pe" has two possible pronunciations of [p] and [f].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Thus for the sound [p], the letter "pe" (פ) is used.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] For the sound [f], the letter "pe" plus Rafe or Geresh (פﬞ (פ׳) / ף) is used.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish, the letter "G" represents two pronunciations.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] If "G" is followed by "e", "i", or "y", it will have a "soft" pronunciation [x].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Otherwise, it will have a hard pronunciation [g].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish, the letter "J" has pronunciation identical with "soft G".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, these two were pronounced as [ʒ‍~d͡ʒ].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Thus, the Aljamiado letter for both these sounds is reflective of this historic sound.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "jim" (ج) is used, as opposed to "khaʾ" (خ).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Similarly in Judeo-Spanish, the letter "gimel" plus Rafe or Geresh (גﬞ (ג׳)) has historically been used.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Modern Judeo-Spanish (Ladino), unlike varieties of Spanish, this historic pronunciation has been preserved.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] However, due to contact and influence from other languages, namely Serbo-Croatian, Turkish, and French, a distinction between [ʒ‍] and [d͡ʒ] in orthography has come to dominance.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Namely that the former ([ʒ‍]) are shown with "zayn" Rafe or Geresh (זﬞ (ז׳)).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Similar to the letter "B", the letter "D" represents two allophones in Spanish.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] If the letter is at the beginning of the word, or after a nasal consonant ("m" or "n"), it is pronounced as [d].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] While this is not reflected in Latin alphabet, in Aljamiado manuscripts, as well as in Judeo-Spanish (not universally) is shown.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In instances where the pronunciation is [d], the letter "dal" (د) has been used in Aljamiado, and the letter "dalet" (ד) Judeo-Spanish.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In instances where the pronunciation is [ð], the letter "ḏal" (ذ) has been used in Aljamiado, and the letter "dalet" plus Rafe or Geresh (דﬞ (ד׳)) Judeo-Spanish.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Spanish Latin Alphabet, "r" versus "rr" denotes a difference in pronunciation, with the former being [ɾ] (Voiced alveolar tap), and the latter [r] (Voiced alveolar trill).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] This distinction is used in Aljamiado too with the use of shadda.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "r" being shown with "raʾ" (ر), and the "rr" with "raʾ-shadda" (رّ).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] This distinction is not shown in Judeo-Spanish.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Both cases are shown with a single "resh" (ר).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In some regional varieties of Ladino, the distinction in pronunciation had ceased to exist as well.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] One of the notable evolutions in the Spanish language has been with respect to fricative-coronal consonants.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, the letter "z" was pronounced as [d͡z].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] It is thus written in Aljamiado with the letter "zaʾ" (ز).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish, the letter "zayin" (ז) is used.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] However, in modern Spanish, the pronunciation of the letter "z" has evolved in two manners.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In most dialects of European Spanish, the letter "z" today is pronounced identically as the soft pronunciation of the letter "c", as [θ].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Latin American dialects, the letter "z" is pronounced identically as the letter "s" and the soft pronunciation of the letter "c", as [s].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The letter "c" has two pronunciations in Spanish, based on rules and factors, hard and soft C.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] "c" is pronounced "soft" if it is followed by "e", "i", or "y", or if it is given a cedilla accent (ç).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In other cases, "c" is pronounced as "hard", as a [k].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, the soft pronunciation of "c" was as [t͡s].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Aljamiado, this letter was uniquely assigned the letter "sin" (س).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish, the letter "samech" (ס) was used.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] However, in modern Spanish, the soft pronunciation of the letter "c" has evolved in two manners.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In most dialects of European Spanish, the letter "c" today is pronounced identically as the letter "z", as [θ].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Latin American dialects, the soft pronunciation of the letter "c" is pronounced identically as the letter "s" and "z", as [s].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, the letter "s" was pronounced as [s] or [z], distinct from the soft pronunciation of the letter "c".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The digraph "ss" represented [s] as well, but has since been replaced with a single "s" in Spanish orthography.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] To reflect the difference between "s" and soft pronunciation of "c", in Aljamiado, the letter "shin" (ش) was given a new association and sound, and was used to write "s".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Similarly, in Judeo-Spanish, letter "shin" (ש) was used.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In modern Judeo-Spanish, in the centuries after expulsion of Jews from Spain, as the pronunciations of "c" and "s" merged independently of Spanish, confusion ensued for a few decades, with both "samech" (ס) and "shin" (ש) being used interchangeably.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] Today, the letter "samech" (ס) has won out and is used exclusively.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In old Spanish, the letter "x" had a pronunciation as [ʃ].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Aljamiado, the letter "shin" (ش) was used.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish, the letter "shin" has been used, historically with niqqud Rafe or Geresh (שﬞ (ש׳)).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In modern Spanish, the pronunciation of "x" has evolved.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In most cases, it is now pronounced as the letter "j" would, [x].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] This is reflected in orthography as well.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish, the original pronunciation has been retained.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In some instances, especially in beginning of words as "ex-", the letter "x" has preserved an [s] sound, or a [ks] sound.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] In Judeo-Spanish this is reflected mostly by "gimel+zayin" (גז) and in some other words as "koph+samech" (קס).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/aljamiado] The practice of Jews writing Romance languages such as Spanish, Aragonese or Catalan in the Hebrew script is also referred to as *aljamiado*.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The **Bashkir alphabet** (Bashkir: Башҡорт әлифбаһы, romanized: *Başqort əlifbahı*) is a writing system used for the Bashkir language.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Until the mid-19th century, Bashkir speakers wrote in the Volga Türki literary language using the Arabic script.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] In 1869, Russian linguist Mirsalikh Bekchurin published the first guide to Bashkir grammar, and the first Cyrillic Bashkir introductory book was published by Vasily Katarinsky in Orenburg in 1892.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Latinisation was first discussed in June 1924, when the first draft of the Bashkir alphabet using the Latin script was created.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] More reforms followed, culminating in the final version in 1938.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Many works of Bashkir literature were written in Volga Türki, including *Bashkir shezhere* ("Genealogies of the Bashkir People"), Batyrsha's *Letter to Empress Elizaveta*, the orders of Salawat Yulayev, as well as works from the poets A.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Kargaly, Tadgetdin Yalsigul Al-Bashkordi, H.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Salikhov, Gali Sokoroy, Miftahetdin Akmulla, and Mukhametsalim Umetbaev.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The influence of spoken Bashkir is noticeable in many works from the period.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The first attempts to create a writing system that fully represented the Bashkir language began in the middle of the 19th century, with writers attempting to adapt the Cyrillic alphabet.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] One such proponent was turkologist and linguist Nikolay Ilminsky, in his work *Introductory Reading in the Turkish-Tatar Language Course*.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] In 1869, Russian linguist Mirsalikh Bekchurin published the first guide to Bashkir grammar in the book *An Initial Guide to the Study of Arabic, Persian and Tatar Languages with the Adverbs of Bukhara, Bashkirs, Kyrgyz and Residents of Turkestan*.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The first Cyrillic Bashkir introductory book was published by Vasily Katarinsky in Orenburg in 1892, with his proposed alphabet excluding the letters ё, й, ѳ, and ѵ from the contemporaneous Cyrillic alphabet and including the additional characters of Ä, г̇, ҥ, Ö, ӳ.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Another primer was prepared at the end of the 19th century by Nikolaï Katanov using the umlaut (ӓ – / ә /, ӧ – / ө /, ӟ – / ҙ /, к̈ – / ҡ /, ӱ – / и /, etc.), however this work was never published.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] In 1907, Alexander Bessonov published *The Primer for the Bashkirs*.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] This publication proposed that alphabet included all the letters of the Cyrillic alphabet of the time, except for ё and й, and added the characters ӓ, г̣, д̣, ҥ, ӧ, с̣, and ӱ.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Five years later, Mstislav Kulaev (Mukhametkhan Kulaev) published *The Basics of Onomatopoeia and the Alphabet for Bashkirs* (reprinted in 1919), again making use of the Cyrillic alphabet in conjunction with new characters.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] In July 1921, the 2nd All-Bashkir Congress of Soviets decided to create their own script for Bashkir as the state language of the Bashkir ASSR.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] In December 1922, the Congress formed a commission for the development of a new official alphabet and spelling at the ASSR's Academic Center of the People's Commissariat of Education.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] This alphabet remained in use until the official adoption of Latin alphabet in 1930.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The commission adapted the Arabic alphabet to the needs of Bashkir phonology.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The commission excluded some letters and normalized the spelling of vowels.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] During the conference, 3 proposals came to be considered, "Old orthography / Iśke imlä", "Middle orthography / Urta imlä", and "New orthography / Yaña imlä".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Old orthography was the existing old Bashkir written tradition that was in use for centuries in Bashkortostan.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Middle orthography was a middle-ground modification that proposed modifying the alphabet to match Bashkir phonology, but not too radically.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] This orthography is to have 6 vowels, and rely on context or a marker for indicating the specific vowel sounds of each word.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Its proponents argued that this orthography would be the most realistic, and it will be the easiest to implement.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] "New orthography" proposed a radical modification, specifically to add 9 vowels.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] At the end of the day, "New orthography" was deemed too unrealistic to implement, as printing presses in the region did not have the required letter types.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Thus "middle orthography" was adopted and was referred to as "New orthography / Yaña imlä" in contrast with the old.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The new writing system used a *hamza on ya* (ئـ‌ ئ) at the beginning of words that start with vowels.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The alphabet underwent several minor iterations of changes and updates to the orthographic conventions between 1924 and 1930.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Similar to other Turkic languages, Bashkir has vowel harmony rules.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Bashkir orthography has two-dimensional vowel harmony rules, front versus back vowels, and rounded versus unrounded vowels.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] There are 9 vowel sounds in Bashkir, but the orthography only offers 6 letters (ئا، ئە، یـ، ىُـ، و، ۇ).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Thus in order to determine how a vowel letter is pronounced, reliance, either on a special diacritic, or on word context is required.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The logic essentially is that low alef indicates that the vowels of the word are articulated in the same part of the mouth as an [ɑ] sound, which is written with an alif ⟨ ئا / ا‎ ⟩, i.e. at back of the mouth.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Hamza plays a similar but inverse role in Kazakh Arabic Alphabet, marking that vowels in a word will be front vowels.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] There are exceptions in Bashkir orthography, meaning words that will have back vowels, but won't have low alef written for them.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] First are words that contain the vowel *alef* **А а (A a)** (shown in Arabic Script as ئا / ا / ـا).
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] This vowel is a back vowel, and its corresponding front vowel pair is written with a different letter altogether.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Thus, it is an unambiguous conclusion that any word containing alef, will have all its other vowels as back vowels too.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Thus, the *low alef* will be redundant, and so it's not written.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] For example, the word *йорт (yort)*, meaning "house", is written with low alef, as **ࢭیۇرت** .
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] But in its plural form, *йорттар (yorttar)* is written as **یۇرتتار**.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Inversely, words that contain the vowel *Ә ә (Ä ä)* (shown in Arabic Script as ئە / ـە / ە) or *И и (İ i)* (shown in Arabic Script as ئیـ / ـیـ / ی) are unambiguously words in which all vowels will be front vowels.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] As per Bashkir phonology, the letters **Г г (G g)** (گ) and **К к (K k)** (ك) can only be accompanied by front vowels.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Thus there won't be any words containing these consonants that would need low alef.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] In contrast, the letters **Ғ ғ (Ğ ğ)** (ع) and **Ҡ ҡ (Q q)** (ق) can only be accompanied by back vowels.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] This means that they themselves act as indicators that vowels in a word are back vowels, thus eliminating a need for low alef.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] For example, the word *йылы (yılı)*, meaning "warm", is written as **ࢭیلىُ**, whereas, a derived word, such as *йылылыҡ / yılılıq*, meaning "heat", is written as **یلىُلق**.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The rejected "New orthography / Yaña imlä" proposal would not have had reliance on such orthographic conventions as those mentioned above for the actually adopted "Middle orthography".
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Instead, this orthography was to have 9 vowels, one per each sound, as shown on the below table.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The Bashkir ASSR Academic Center began discussing Latinisation in June 1924 and drafted a Bashkir alphabet using the Latin script later that year.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] In June 1927, the All-Union Committee of the New Turkic alphabet approved a single alphabet for the Turkic peoples of the USSR; Yañalif, with the additional letters Đ đ [ð] and Ѣ ѣ [θ].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The Bashkir Latinized alphabet was again revised to align with this standard, and on 6 July 1930, the Central Executive Committee of the Bashkir ASSR officially approved the new revision.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] In May 1933, at the conference of the Bashkir Scientific Research Institute of Language and Literature, the letter Ç ç was removed.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] The digraph *ьj* was similarly eliminated in 1938.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Today Bashkir Latin alphabet based on the Common Turkic alphabet is in use.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] It has 2 additional letters, representing special consonant sounds Đđ [ð] and Ŧŧ [θ].
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Барлыҡ кешеләр ирекле, дәрәжәләре һәм хоҡуҡтары тигеҙ булып тыуалар. Улар аҡыл һәм выждан эйәһе һәм бер-береһенә ҡарата ҡәрҙәшлек рухында хәрәкәт итергә тейештәр.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Barlıq keşelər irekle, dərəjələre həm xoquqtarı tigeź bulıp tıwalar.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] Ular aqıl həm vıjdan eyəhe həm ber-berehenə qarata qərźəşlek ruxında xərəkət itergə teyeştər.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] All human beings are born free and equal in dignity and rights.
[src:bashkir-alphabet/bashkir-alphabet] They are endowed with reason and conscience and should act towards one another in a spirit of brotherhood.
